{
  "key_observation": "In complex coordinates with the circumcircle as the unit circle, the three vertices of the reflected-line triangle are the images of a, b, c under one Möbius transformation, and the image circle meets the unit circle in a double point.",
  "plan": [
    "Normalize the circumcircle to the unit circle in the complex plane.",
    "Write the tangent at p and compute the equations of its reflections in the sides of ABC.",
    "Solve for the three intersection points a1, b1, c1 and recognize them as values of one Möbius map.",
    "Compute the image circle of the unit circle under this Möbius map.",
    "Show that its intersection with the original unit circle is a double point.",
    "Conclude that the two circles are tangent, hence their centers and their common point are collinear."
  ],
  "steps": [
    {
      "claim": "We may assume that the circumcircle o of ABC is the unit circle in the complex plane, with complex coordinates a, b, c, p satisfying |a|=|b|=|c|=|p|=1.",
      "reasoning": "A direct similarity transformation preserves reflections, tangencies, circles, and collinearity of centers. Thus it is enough to prove the result after sending o to the unit circle.",
      "facts_used": [
        "similarity transformations preserve circles",
        "similarity transformations preserve reflections",
        "similarity transformations preserve collinearity"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The tangent line to the unit circle at p has equation z+p^2\\overline z=2p.",
      "reasoning": "The usual tangent equation at a point p on the unit circle is \\overline p z+p\\overline z=2. Since |p|=1, multiplying by p gives z+p^2\\overline z=2p.",
      "facts_used": [
        "tangent line equation to the unit circle",
        "|p|=1"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "If u and v are two points of the unit circle, then the reflection of the tangent line z+p^2\\overline z=2p across the chord uv has equation p^2z+u^2v^2\\overline z=(u+v)(uv+p^2)-2puv.",
      "reasoning": "Reflection in the line through unit points u and v sends a point z to u+v-uv\\overline z. Substituting z=u+v-uv\\overline w into the tangent equation and then renaming w as z gives the displayed equation.",
      "facts_used": [
        "reflection formula across a chord of the unit circle",
        "step 2"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "Let s=a+b+c, t=ab+bc+ca, and u=abc. Then the intersection point a1 of the two reflected tangent lines across CA and AB has complex coordinate α=f(a), where f(r)=\\frac{t-2u/p+(u/p^2)r}{s-r}. Similarly, b1 and c1 have coordinates β=f(b) and γ=f(c).",
      "reasoning": "For a1, use the equations from step 3 with (u,v)=(c,a) and (u,v)=(a,b). Subtracting them gives \\overline α=\\frac{a(s-2p)+p^2}{a^2(s-a)}, and conjugating, using |a|=|b|=|c|=|p|=1, gives α=\\frac{t-2abc/p+(abc/p^2)a}{s-a}. The formulas for β and γ follow cyclically.",
      "facts_used": [
        "step 3",
        "|a|=|b|=|c|=|p|=1",
        "cyclic symmetry"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The circle o1 through a1, b1, c1 is the image of the unit circle under the Möbius transformation f(r)=\\frac{t-2u/p+(u/p^2)r}{s-r}.",
      "reasoning": "By step 4, the three points a1, b1, c1 are f(a), f(b), f(c). A Möbius transformation sends a circle or line to a circle or line; since a1, b1, c1 determine the circle o1, that image circle is precisely o1.",
      "facts_used": [
        "step 4",
        "Möbius transformations send generalized circles to generalized circles"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "A point z lies on o1 if and only if |sz-(t-2u/p)|=|z+u/p^2|.",
      "reasoning": "Solving z=f(r) for r gives r=\\frac{sz-(t-2u/p)}{z+u/p^2}. Since o1 is the image of the unit circle under f, z lies on o1 exactly when the corresponding r satisfies |r|=1, which is equivalent to the displayed equation.",
      "facts_used": [
        "step 5",
        "definition of the unit circle",
        "inverse of a Möbius transformation"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The intersection of o1 with the original unit circle is a double point.",
      "reasoning": "Assume |z|=1, so \\overline z=1/z. Squaring out the equation from step 6 gives (sz-(t-2u/p))(\\overline s-\\overline{t-2u/p}\\,z)=(z+u/p^2)(1+\\overline{u/p^2}\\,z). Using \\overline s=t/u, \\overline t=s/u, \\overline u=1/u, and \\overline p=1/p, this reduces to -\\frac{1}{u}\\left((s-p)z-u\\left(\\overline s-\\frac1p\\right)\\right)^2=0. Hence the intersection equation has one double root.",
      "facts_used": [
        "step 6",
        "|z|=1 implies \\overline z=1/z",
        "|a|=|b|=|c|=|p|=1",
        "algebraic expansion"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The circles o and o1 are tangent at their unique common point x.",
      "reasoning": "Two circles meet tangentially exactly when their intersection equation has a double root. By step 7, o and o1 have one common point counted with multiplicity two, so they are tangent there. Therefore every point x lying on both circles is this tangency point.",
      "facts_used": [
        "step 7",
        "criterion for tangency of two circles by double intersection"
      ]
